commit_message:
Add -constraints sections for base CI jobs

Using factors with sections is not a thing and likely will not be for
a while, as such we are going to have to duplicate sections to be able
to set the constraints based install_command.

Implements Blueprint: Requirements-Management

Change-Id: Ie679904330a83e4b7eb75c189b48afef127b0d22
(cherry picked from commit 44905578fdf95373f4bc3b3f0693892eb30e74d3)

commit_message:
Fix python-jobs

The thing is that nailgun tests require postgresql backend to
be available. So, we need to prepare it before running tests.
Fortunately, all unit tests are run on nodes where postgresql
is installed.

Change-Id: Idc14409d2b2d3473d0e3ef9d3e70bda57a331b11

commit_message:
Always default to InnoDB for MySQL

OpenStack CI uses MyISAM by default, which does not even support
foreign keys. This change essentially mirrors what ironic is doing.

Also sets the default charset to UTF-8.

Closes-Bug: #1506160
Change-Id: I7caf0a2122f98c59f121f003ac092ecb0ce123c4
(cherry picked from commit fbfdf5ee694bad4ab22dfa52d601c74e899c8c1b)

commit_message:
Rescue boots to SMS

Previously, the PowerVM power_on Job was broken for bootmode='sms', so
the rescue flow skipped this step, leaving it to the user to boot to SMS
manually.  The power_on Job now works, so this change set restores the
boot step to the rescue flow.

Change-Id: I71e28dcbb96ae580ac3ebb54582eee9a039b9ae6

[{'created': '2015-07-01 19:12:41.000000000', 'message': "rootwrap: update ln --symbolic filter for FS and FC type volume drivers

Cinder change I03f8cae05cc117e14f7482115de685fc9f3fa54a sets the
'encrypted' key for all cinder volume drivers connection_info. When run
through the encrypted volume tests in Tempest, this hits the encryption
providers in Nova that fail for certain types of volume drivers, like
file system and fibre channel, due to the rootwrap filter not matching.

This change updates the symbolic link rootwrap filter so it works with
file system and fibre channel type volume backends rather than just
iSCSI.

The /dev/mapper/ prefix is always set in the encryptor modules, so that
can remain as before.

The symbolic link path is a complete wildcard, however, because the file
system volume backends all have a configurable option for the mount path
prefix, which defaults to $state_path/mnt but may not be that value.

An example call for NFS:

ln --symbolic --force \
/dev/mapper/volume-f5684ecc-959f-4de8-8d62-a8adf4bdb4cc \
/opt/stack/data/nova/mnt/21dd48babac42ae884d1192b8697a041/\

ln --symbolic --force \
/dev/mapper/pci-0000:06:00.0-fc-0x5006016508603f9f-lun-151 \
/dev/disk/by-path/pci-0000:06:00.0-fc-0x5006016508603f9f-lun-151

This change also updates the sg_info and sgscan entries to reference the
correct module since those are not called from nova.virt.libvirt.volume
anymore.

Closes-Bug: #1470142
Related-Bug: #1440227

commit_message:
rootwrap: update ln --symbolic filter for FS and FC type volume drivers

Cinder change I03f8cae05cc117e14f7482115de685fc9f3fa54a sets the
'encrypted' key for all cinder volume drivers connection_info. When run
through the encrypted volume tests in Tempest, this hits the encryption
providers in Nova that fail for certain types of volume drivers, like
file system and fibre channel, due to the rootwrap filter not matching.

This change updates the symbolic link rootwrap filter so it works with
file system and fibre channel type volume backends rather than just
iSCSI.

The /dev/mapper/ prefix is always set in the encryptor modules, so that
can remain as before.

The symbolic link path is a complete wildcard, however, because the file
system volume backends all have a configurable option for the mount path
prefix, which defaults to $state_path/mnt but may not be that value.

An example call for NFS:

ln --symbolic --force \
/dev/mapper/volume-f5684ecc-959f-4de8-8d62-a8adf4bdb4cc \
/opt/stack/data/nova/mnt/21dd48babac42ae884d1192b8697a041/\
volume-f5684ecc-959f-4de8-8d62-a8adf4bdb4cc

An example call for fibre channel:

ln --symbolic --force \
/dev/mapper/pci-0000:06:00.0-fc-0x5006016508603f9f-lun-151 \
/dev/disk/by-path/pci-0000:06:00.0-fc-0x5006016508603f9f-lun-151

This change also updates the sg_info and sgscan entries to reference the
correct module since those are not called from nova.virt.libvirt.volume
anymore.

Closes-Bug: #1470142
Related-Bug: #1440227

Change-Id: I181b594a3119f7ad74c595fc7059d521079b1d74

Updating Contrail Plugin test suite.

Add possibility to work with Open and Juniper distribution
and add additional time for node waiting necessary
for Contrail specific deployment.

commit_message:
Add backwards compat for Keystone name_length

The name_length argument was removed from a number of Keystone
scenarios in
https://github.com/openstack/rally/commit/e862f86e3f8f6c0770a53cf4772f9b8b6df388d5,
but it should have been logged and ignored instead of completely
removed. This restores the argument, along with a log message that it
isn't used.

Implements: blueprint consistent-resource-names
Change-Id: Ice0fc24392c795598c97fa8cc4c0644d5dce7ac7

Fix versionchanged

The change I9b806efc750009d64b08a5583449bebbf10e3fb4 was documented
for the version 2.6 but it was merged after the release 2.6. So the

commit_message:
Do not initialize/manage keystone in python-tripleoclient

Current initialization of keystone and endpoint,service,role creation is
delegated to python-tripleoclient. Those actions can be done in puppet
using the upstream module. This allows to leverage all the work already
done in the upstream modules.

Change-Id: I95023094da0d7d3d9a05a8479d7394dba8be12b6
Depends-On: I50e792d98a2ba516ff498c58ad402f463c5f7e76

commit_message:
Move cinder_catalog_info to init

In a previous commit, we introduced cinder_catalog_info parameter but it
was a mistake to configure it on nova api class, because this parameter
is also used by nova compute.

cinder_catalog_info is a parameter used by nova/volume/cinder.py in
cinderclient method, consummed by nova compute manager code.

This patch is non-backward compatible but it does not matter because it
was not in the latest stable release and has not been backported.

Change-Id: Id9e579ca31364d5207d0c1b892d0f7aa7f20f7a8

commit_message:
OpenStackClient plugin for stack show

This change was derived from Id188cdc0e97b480875a7626443f68e69863f0647
which added stack support to python-openstackclient, but adapting it
to be an openstackclient plugin which lives in the python-heatclient
tree.

This change only implements the "openstack stack show". Subsequent
commands will remain in WIP changes at the end of this series until they
are ready to merge.

The stack show formatting has the following behaviour:
- specifying key order for important values, but adding all other
  stack keys in default order (future proofing for new values)
- exclude template_description, its a dupe of 'description'
- complex values like parameters, outputs and links get a special formatter
  depending on the output format ('table' formats them as yaml,
  'shell', 'value', 'html' formats them as json)

Co-Authored-By: Ryan S. Brown <rybrown@redhat.com>
Co-Authored-By: Rico Lin <rico.l@inwinstack.com>
Change-Id: I3096b94146a94d184c29b8c7c9f6c032eed5281d

commit_message:
Always copy clouds.yaml to jenkins user

As more and more programs use clouds.yaml as a source of cloud config
for their tests, they're all having to copy the file from devstack
to jenkins. As clouds.yaml is a thing that devstack always produces,
there's no good reason to not add it to the jenkins user and make it
easy for people to consume.

Change-Id: I7acfdd079e753bc7290463e66a065cc595093fbb

(6 comments)

Detailed thoughts inline, but overall I think the spec addresses my concerns about feature backports that were discussed in the meeting today.  However, I'm pretty strongly -1 on the idea of _requiring_ backports.  If there's enough interest in a feature to backport it then great, but requiring it for all features is too much IMHO.

Keep in mind that the reality all of the other OpenStack projects are dealing with is that there is barely enough interest in the upstream stable branches to even keep them passing CI most of the time, much less backporting features.  Forcing new contributors (and our limited number of core reviewers) to deal with that process is a significant barrier to entry that I don't think we need."}, {'account_id': 7144, 'date': '2015-09-22 17:35:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

my thoughts around the "require" backport vs "can" backport was that if it's not a requirement, and only a "can", then this is exactly what enables 90% of the folks to ignore the stable brances, and why people don't care about them.

would there really  be the lack of interest in the stable branches in the other projects, if it was a requirement to get your backport merged there as well?

so, i suppose i'm ok with dropping the requirement part, I just really want to know who's going to be maintaining them. And, if there will be some who choose to outright ignore them if they don't use them.

as long as there is some set of folks saying they're going to maintain the branches, i'm ok with dropping the requirement part.'}, {'account_id': 12715, 'date': '2015-09-22 18:07:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

My only concern with this is similar to slagle, namely: Where are the resources for this going to come from?

The current workload is probably a bit exaggerated because of the recent imports and changing of the CI to use them, but it seems that there is a lack of resources for even the current workload.

I do not think it will help us gain wider adoption to have a poorly maintained stable branch that is rarely functional.'}, {'account_id': 6928, 'date': '2015-09-22 22:26:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

If people don't have time to deal with stable branches when it's optional, all forcing it will accomplish is to reduce the amount of work they can get done on master.  I guess that's one way to ensure maintained stable branches, but it also seems like a good way to scare off new contributors and reduce our ability to keep up with new features in the first place (iow, not having to do dual maintenance by supporting things right away, which is the ideal situation).

Given that I think we're going to have a vested interest in the stable branches (presumably we'll be basing downstream products on them), if we can't be bothered to maintain them then nobody will.

Also, I still think feature backports should be the exception rather than the rule.  As I noted inline, we have the ability to hold our release until the important features are done, and the more stuff we backport to the "stable" branch the more likely we are to introduce instability.

I could probably go on (how many releases are we going to require backports for?), but I've convinced myself so I'm going to stop now. :-)'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2015-09-23 06:54:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

> would there really be the lack of interest in the stable branches in the other projects, if it was a requirement to get your backport merged there as well?

This is actually a point against the "require" thing though - all other projects manage to have functional stable branches without mandating that contributors do backports.

Yes, invariably the backport effort falls on a small subset of stable-maint folks, who invariably work for one or more downstream consumers of those branches, but at least the effort is happening in an upstream location where multiple downstream consumers can combine efforts and share the load (I know that's not really a thing for TripleO, yet), and everything can be tested and kept working via upstream CI (including grenade testing of upgrades etc).'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2015-09-23 07:27:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

> My only concern with this is similar to slagle, namely: Where are the resources for this going to come from?

Honestly, the same place it does now - we're already maintaining branches like this for rdo-manager, so it's a question of reducing that branch workload and shifting some of the effort more upstream.

My hope by having a consumable upstream branch is that we also engage upstream contributors (and users) over time to more proactively propose backports, rather than it all being driven by downstream users and package maintainers.

> I do not think it will help us gain wider adoption to have a poorly maintained stable branch that is rarely functional.

That's true - if we do this the branch *must* be CI tested, otherwise this whole effort will be pointless.

The counter argument is that if we never have an upstream TripleO that can actually deploy the user/operator-orientated stable OpenStack releases, we can be pretty much certain we will never get wider adoption beyond the developer community.  

So, having a release model which specifically excludes nearly all (non trunk-chasing) operators is not a healthy way to build a community around a project, IMHO."}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2015-09-23 10:57:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

(2 comments)'}, {'account_id': 7144, 'date': '2015-09-23 19:18:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Ben has made some really good points, and I dont want this to be blocked on the disagreement. Particularly, the new contributor aspect may trump any reason to "require" the backport, and wasn't something I was fully considering. Thanks for pointing that out, and continuing to harp on it :).

I do struggle a bit with seeing where the resources to maintain the branches is going to come from. As that's really at the crux of my review about asking for the requirement, if we're instead saying we have the resources (or at least reasonably confident we do), then I'm on board with removing the harder language on the requirement nature that I originally asked for.

As for the rdo-manager downstream branch:

> My only concern with this is similar to slagle, namely: Where are the resources for this going to come from?

>> Honestly, the same place it does now - we're already maintaining branches like this for rdo-manager, so it's a question of reducing that branch workload and shifting some of the effort more upstream.

Well, the reality is that we had to abandon the rdo-manager branches and they are no longer maintained ... due to lack of resources. So, these types of patterns is the mindset of where I was coming from.

I am fully on board though with saying we are going to try this again, have it be upstream, and double down on our effort to pull it off right this time.'}, {'account_id': 6928, 'date': '2015-09-23 19:41:59.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

(1 comment)

> I do struggle a bit with seeing where the resources to maintain the branches is going to come from. As that's really at the crux of my review about asking for the requirement, if we're instead saying we have the resources (or at least reasonably confident we do), then I'm on board with removing the harder language on the requirement nature that I originally asked for.

If we don't have the resources (which is a big part of my concern - mandatory backports increase everyone's workload by some non-trivial amount), then we don't have the resources though, right?  Or is your concern that we have the necessary resources but they aren't be prioritized correctly?  If the latter, then I would be willing to reconsider, but I'm not convinced it's the case.  As you said, even with corporate overlords handing down decrees about maintaining what amounted to a stable branch, we still couldn't do it effectively.  Dual maintenance is a huge burden.

s/resources/people/ in this entire comment.  I hate myself now. :-P"}, {'account_id': 7144, 'date': '2015-09-24 20:05:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

> If we don't have the resources (which is a big part of my concern - mandatory backports increase everyone's workload by some non-trivial amount), then we don't have the resources though, right? Or is your concern that we have the necessary resources but they aren't be prioritized correctly? If the latter, then I would be willing to reconsider, but I'm not convinced it's the case. As you said, even with corporate overlords handing down decrees about maintaining what amounted to a stable branch, we still couldn't do it effectively. Dual maintenance is a huge burden.

I don't want increased burden on just the usual people I see fixing stuff upstream. If the stable branches come with more people to help maintain them, that would be great. There are a few non-core folks who have taken the time to review this spec -- trown has also been killing it helping out with CI recently :). That is awesome to see.

But, one or 2 new folks isn't enough for this effort IMO.

So, who are we signing up to maintain the branches? It's that simple to me.

Who is saying they are maintaining the branches?

Can we assume whoever +1's or +2's this spec is saying they will help? I know it can't be everyone's top priority, but if we can get a decent enough group, then it doesn't have to be just any one or two persons top priority, b/c the responsibility will be shared.

I'm going to +2 this spec with or without the requirement, and am going to help with the maintenance. My ask around the requirement was to find a way to spread the responsibility. If it's just agreed upon to be spread around, that would work as well. If it's not spread out at all, then I dont think this effort will be successful. But, even in that case, I am on board with trying it."}, {'account_id': 11234, 'date': '2015-09-25 08:54:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2015-09-28 17:22:15.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2015-09-28 17:23:56.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-09-28 17:29:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Verified+1

commit_message:
Use hashlib instead of md5

As md5 lib has been deprecated, we should use hashlib.md5() instead
of md5.new()

Change-Id: I5c49a97267be352f0160758880982c8ab0385064

commit_message:
If mongodb_replica_set is empty do not pass it to client

Otherwise a replicaSet parameter in a db connection URL will be
clobbered by the empty configuration setting.

Note that this is a direct patch to stable/liberty, not a backport from
master because master has changed such that there is no longer a
mongodb_replica_set configuration setting.

Change-Id: Ic8de93f58ff1cf21888719597490f987d703cab6
Closes-Bug: #1505669

updated.

commit_message:
Add retries to nova_admin_tenant_id_setter

Add up to ten retries before raising an exception to avoid failure in case
when Keystone is temporarily unavailable due to connectivity or other problems

Co-Authored-By: Dmitry Ilyin <@dilyin@mirantis.com>
Change-Id: I5c07d31aa51a73fb0d870af81c6581559361450b
Closes-bug: #1467957

commit_message:
[WIP] Add --root parameter to configuration directory

The --root parameter specifies the location of
undercloud-passwords.conf and .ssh
A separate patch must be added to be able to specify the location
of undercloud-env.json, as it's currently hardcoded to the local
directory only, but not by python-tripleoclient.

Change-Id: I5c809b965e2ca1074b419e3db0c560409b91b444
Closes-Bug: https://bugzilla.redhat.com/show_bug.cgi?id=1250849

messages:
[{'account_id': 18238, 'date': '2015-10-20 04:31:38.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-20 04:38:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-mistral-dashboard-pep8 http://logs.openstack.org/90/237390/1/check/gate-mistral-dashboard-pep8/e3483ef/ : SUCCESS in 1m 37s
- gate-mistral-dashboard-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/90/237390/1/check/gate-mistral-dashboard-docs/ef68d92//doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 1m 32s
- gate-mistral-dashboard-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/90/237390/1/check/gate-mistral-dashboard-python27/0104776/ : SUCCESS in 2m 06s
- gate-mistral-dashboard-python34 http://logs.openstack.org/90/237390/1/check/gate-mistral-dashboard-python34/ce4674c/ : FAILURE in 2m 40s (non-voting)'}, {'account_id': 9432, 'date': '2015-10-20 04:53:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

hm... why is this a problem? 1) it may be .yml 2) we may call mistral DSL .mist and most importantly it may be .yaml that contains garbage. if we want to check on a client, do parse yaml.

The right fix IMO is good response coming from the server. This will do good to all clients, not just dashboard.'}, {'account_id': 18238, 'date': '2015-10-20 05:09:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Error message shows on screen is not clear when invalid
file is uploaded.

So I think we should notify user that file he/she want
to upload is invalid. ".yaml" or ".yml" file format should be
uploaded.'}, {'account_id': 8731, 'date': '2015-10-20 10:19:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

I completely disagree with this patch for the reasons that Dmitri already mentioned. We do not specify anywhere that it users must keep Mistral artefacts (workbooks/workflows/actions) in files with extension ".yaml". It's totally irrelevant from a service perspective and 100% up to a user. As far as validation in general, it is too complicated so that we could do it on a client side. Look at mistral/workbook module, most of the code in there is about validation. My point here is that since it's complicated we shouldn't spread it out between components, it should be at one place. So the right resolution of this bug would be properly displaying a message from a server.'}, {'account_id': 18238, 'date': '2015-10-20 12:19:13.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-10-19 17:07:40.000000000', 'message': 'Added rotating logging to the neutron ha tool

This change adds a local logger for the neutron ha tool.
The logger is /var/log/neutron but will fall back to the users
home folder if needed. This will make possible to track actions
of the tool when needed in a fail over scenario.

Change-Id: I91df7a17138661d7bb0692c23ed93ea6a2e774e2

commit_message:
Added rotating logging to the neutron ha tool

This change adds a local logger for the neutron ha tool.
The logger is /var/log/neutron but will fall back to the users
home folder if needed. This will make possible to track actions
of the tool when needed in a fail over scenario.

Change-Id: I91df7a17138661d7bb0692c23ed93ea6a2e774e2
Closes-bug: #1411260
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>
(cherry picked from commit 20481eaa207bc764d9624ea5cb61f605f395a01c)

Added rotating logging to the neutron ha tool

This change adds a local logger for the neutron ha tool.
The logger is /var/log/neutron but will fall back to the users
home folder if needed. This will make possible to track actions
of the tool when needed in a fail over scenario.

Closes-bug: #1411260
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>

commit_message:
Fix to correctly set the nova_management_address

This change sets the nova management address based on the
facts the play is able to set about the environment.

This will correct configure the nova to use a specific
management network which is not always the default
container address.

Closes-Bug: #1504226
Change-Id: Ib6d84072d379118ebfc560f4594c28e1fecf3b40
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>
(cherry picked from commit c506dda61d303735189abbee7c70d972b3096a40)
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>

commit_message:
Ensure that the vnc console is disabled when spice is enabled

The spice and vnc consoles are mutually exclusive with Horizon set
to auto-detect the console type. It is also clear from the
configuration method that the designed implementation is to deploy
only one of them.

This patch ensures that only one is enabled at a time by explicitly
disabling the vnc console (which defaults to enabled).

Change-Id: Ib0368d3d6125e4abe7f9a9c40748457fc0d349f2

commit_message:
Always default to InnoDB for MySQL

OpenStack CI uses MyISAM by default, which does not even support
foreign keys. This change essentially mirrors what ironic is doing.

Also sets the default charset to UTF-8.

Closes-Bug: #1506160
Change-Id: I7caf0a2122f98c59f121f003ac092ecb0ce123c4

commit_message:
Disable autostart for tgt and prevent it running

  In case if ceph is selected  as a cinder-volume backend. On the
node running under Ubuntu tgt will be disabled and installed
without starting service

Change-Id: I238bfb59dc62f641f634e662af8cd9de654511c3
Closes-bug:#1491518

commit_message:
Correct OS_IDENTITY_API_VERSION 

The OS_IDENTITY_API_VERSION need to be set to 2.0 instead of 2 when
using the Keystone Identity API version 2. Other settings are currently
not affected

Change-Id: I574bf1c1e908833b139a14b1f402df8db837344b
Closes-Bug: #1506231
(cherry picked from commit 1844a27a89d9f0f0636ed174735714cb26e13363)

commit_message:
Support RYU versions compatibility in DHCP handling

The newest version of RYU convert the payload into
DHCP object, the older version did not. Check if it
is converted or a string. In case that it is a string
convert to DHCP object.

Change-Id: I5594daa3834bd7045f084c567b10261c30fe5799
Closes-Bug: #1507506

Remove StandardError for Python3

As in python3 the StandardError exception has been removed, we
should use BaseException instead of it.

commit_message:
Refactor upgrade_controlplane parts

* move network related methods from `upgrade_controlplane` to `env`
  module
* collect yaml files from nodes if bup info is not present
* extract `delete_overlay_networks` action to separate function

Change-Id: I476a4f7fe884500e7d0c4c401cdeeb8c9af46e63

commit_message:
Add proxy for k8s

This patch adds proxy in follow places:

1. etcd needs ETCD_DISCOVERY_PROXY when try to do discovery
   /etc/etcd/etcd.conf
2. docker daemon need set proxy to allow downloads images
   /etc/systemd/system/docker.service.d/proxy.conf
3. and for os level, we need to set http_proxy, https_proxy and no_proxy too
   /etc/bashrc

Implements: blueprint discovery-proxy
Co-authored-by:  Manjeet Singh Bhatia <manjeet.s.bhatia@intel.com>
Change-Id: I19c92dc9b4fe195037b5ad4ca49b529cf6be4cfb

commit_message:
Add the introduce of the command "magnum help ca-sign"

Currently, when executing "magnum help ca-sign", there is only the use
of the commmand and isn't the introduce about the command.

This patch adds the introduce for "magnum help ca-sign"

Change-Id: I6246f7bb9550014b4501cb9eb745cb8dddaaea61
Closes-Bug: #1507873

commit_message:
Search IP--mac pair for mutli-rack deployments

This search need, because in multi-rack deployments there are no
local IP addresses in the master node APIs subnet.

Co-Authored-By: Sergey Vasilenko <svasilenko@mirantis.com>
Change-Id: I33c47273e8b6cb047eddb248e61e3848b6112ffa
Closes-bug: #1499007

commit_message:
Add the introduce of the command "magnum help ca-show"

Currently, when executing "magnum help ca-show", there is only the use
of the commmand and isn't the introduce about the command.

This patch add the introduce of "magnum help ca-show"

Change-Id: I70bcf1ce015c4ee825062ff5bd15f2a21795c0a4
Closes-Bug: #1507874

commit_message:
Changed "amount" to "number" for proper grammar

Changed:

"Disks amount and size" to "Number and size of disks"
"Interfaces amount" to "Number of interfaces"
"Invalid amount of networks" to "Invalid number of networks"

Closes-bug: 1501520

commit_message:
Standardise ownership of *_venv_bin directories

This review standardises the ownership of the *_venv_dir directories by
ensuring all are created as root instead of using the service's user.
This behaviour already exists in the following roles:

- os_aodh
- os_glance
- os_swift

Change-Id: Idab42b83bece3624271780105f6a937eb88c7491

commit_message:
Experimental fedora-22 node for puppet-apply tests

We do this to ensure we will not break our fedora22 jenkins slaves.
Currently experimental since we only have nodes running under RAX.

Add ambari images for sahara-image-elements

Add a job to try the generation of ambari images, just like done for the
other image types.

commit_message:
Refactoring GlusterFS jobs

This patch refactors Cinder-Glusterfs and Manila-Glusterfs job
definitions to use latest devstack-plugin-glusterfs code.

And also renames the job "gate-tempest-dsvm-full-glusterfs*" to
"gate-cinder-tempest-dsvm-glusterfs*".

Change-Id: Id6967499729dfaa12d8a338d8f72471ebc90fb0d

commit_message:
filter() is wrapped around list().

In py2 filter returns list, but in py3
it returns iterator.

Change-Id: I71db21027bab11c8de715d39e71d0f6317a3f9e0
Partially-Implements: blueprint mistral-py3

commit_message:
Remove devstack install job for networking-ovn.

networking-ovn now has a working, voting tempest job.  This old install
job was an early voting job while we worked to get tempest passing and
is no longer needed.

Change-Id: Ic95b0a1f5d61379ec9f5a8d3356adecb65da56db
Signed-off-by: Russell Bryant <rbryant@redhat.com>

open stable/liberty for ceilometer

Remove the special ACLs and allow the normal stable maintenance team for
ceilometer to manage patches in their stable/liberty branch.

commit_message:
Add openstack-resource-agents project

The Pacemaker Resource Agents for OpenStack project is a revitalization
of a long-used unofficial repository which is referenced by the official
OpenStack High Availability guide but no longer maintained:

  https://github.com/madkiss/openstack-resource-agents

All relevant stakeholders (including the original maintainer) have been
consulted and given unanimous support:

  https://github.com/madkiss/openstack-resource-agents/issues/22
  http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-June/067763.html
  http://clusterlabs.org/pipermail/users/2015-June/000732.html
  http://oss.clusterlabs.org/pipermail/pacemaker/2015-June/023649.html

The import is actually from this fork of the origin repository:

  https://github.com/aspiers/openstack-resource-agents

in order to allow replacement of the old stable branches with tags prior
to import.  There are no other differences between the fork and the
original.

New launchpad project is at:

  https://launchpad.net/openstack-resource-agents

Later we'll review the CLA policy, set up some CI (currently there is no
test suite) etc., but for now this is a first step to import the code
and set up the corresponding #openstack-ha IRC channel.

Signed-off-by: Adam Spiers <aspiers@suse.com>

Change-Id: I8917ab2ec3b02d26de0a1881eeb676e63e5725d4

commit_message:
Add a repository for I18n team

The repository is used to store the utilities, assets
and configrations used by I18n team.
For example, list of terminologies and their translations,
scripts for Zanata operations, and etc.

Change-Id: Ia33089e26d26436869a025245e6808a021c587fe

commit_message:
Temporarily remove zuul-cloner before tarball

Neutron -*aas repos use zuul-cloner to install neutron, however,
it does not currently work unless it is in a proposed-change
configuration.  I8f88cb8d1e49255d38c2c75dd226b3027779aa9e fixes
this, but is not yet applied to our images.  In the interim,
remove zuul-cloner so that neutron-*aas tarballs can work as
intended.

This change may be reverted once
I8f88cb8d1e49255d38c2c75dd226b3027779aa9e lands.

Change-Id: I68c4a49e15cf74bc0231d9de1594bafbcd971478

commit_message:
[WIP] Rearrange group_vars/all into a directory with smaller files

Ansible allows group_vars/all to be a directory containing multiple
YAML files with contents that apply to all targets.

This patch re-arranges the group_vars/*.yml files into smaller
files in the group_vars/all directory to reduce merge conflicts
and keep things simpler and more obvious overall.

Change-Id: Ib4442f159cefcd038c4b1f541b9d4fc5d14b7355

The more I think about it, the less I like this proposal.

We don't want to encourage people to upload directly to the storage backend.  So knowing that the communication between glance and the backend is swift+https:// or whatever isn't going to help you, because there's no guarantee that the glance endpoint in your service catalog will actually accept swift+https:// itself.

The whole point of glance is to abstract the differences among the various storage backends.  The image uploader should use whatever scheme is specified in his/her service catalog to perform the upload."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-08-04 15:38:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified+1

Generally all that work started to help fix this bug https://bugs.launchpad.net/horizon/+bug/1476657 Can someone who has any openstack deployment confirm that it's true?
 
As for me, I think it may be a good UI improvement, because, for example, a user wants to add another location from ftp source to existing image, but server rejects his request, because ftp is not supported. Then he tries to add location from filesystem, and this one is rejected, too. So, I think the user has a right to know what external source types currently available in the system, but not guessing and brute forcing them."}, {'account_id': 13686, 'date': '2015-08-06 19:03:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Brian:
The http store is definetively exposed and used by the End User. I would hope that Glance at some point will add other user-facing storage engines, for example SSH and FTP.

For projects implementing user interfaces (for example OpenStack Horizon), having ways to query and detect what the back end supports is crucial.

We could give the user the crude experience of posting data only to have it refused by an error message, but it would be much better to have ways to present this information dynamically with verification as the users types.

I do agree that some of the inards of image storing is not for consumtion by the end user, but some are, so maby we need multiple categories of storage drivers?

A side note and different example for other areas where detailed knowledge from the back-end is necessary is the rbd store. Here we need to expose the full URL of images to other back-end services to make full use of Cephs capabilities. (show_image_direct_url).'}, {'account_id': 5314, 'date': '2015-08-06 19:50:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Thanks, Frode.  I obviously need to think more carefully about this.  A good place to have this discussion will be on the spec to add this API call.'}, {'account_id': 11391, 'date': '2015-08-07 19:43:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

I came up with another 'lightweight' solution, without adding new api call - we can provide this information for a user in error message. For example here https://github.com/openstack/glance/blob/master/glance/api/v1/images.py#L444

There will be something like 'External source is not supported: %s. Supported schemes are: %s'"}, {'account_id': 18791, 'date': '2015-10-12 08:57:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

This code adds the ability to get a list of all
available schemes in glance

[{'created': '2015-06-23 07:32:53.000000000', 'message': "Move filesystem tasks into import subflows

Currently, the base_import flow adds ImportToFS & DeleteFromFS tasks
if at least one subflow is defined. But these tasks are only needed
for introspect & convert subflows. For any other subflow it's
unnecessary.

This patch moves the logic of ordering into the subflows itself.
i.e the sub-flow will determine how to hook their tasks into the
main import flow.

WIP: May need a spec but definitely unit tests

Change-Id: Ia6025695eeb014bad29ab1f2dd1fc12f717ece2f

"}, {'created': '2015-06-24 00:57:40.000000000', 'message': 'WIP: Refactor import flow to be independent of subflow tasks

The base_import flow should be independent of the subflows configured
by an operator. Currently, we add ImportToFS and DeleteFromFS tasks
to the main import flow if at least one subflow is configured. This
patch moves out the addition of these tasks to the subflow itself.

In short, the following are done in this patch:
1. Move ordering logic to subflows.
2. Provide a utility method that adds the fs tasks only
   once in the required order for introspect and convert flows.
3. Use image uri as a runtime input to remove the dependency between
   ImportToStore and ImportToFS. If ImportToFS is used, the provided
   file location will be rebinding as uri.

WIP: May need a spec but definitely unit tests

Change-Id: Ia6025695eeb014bad29ab1f2dd1fc12f717ece2f
'}, {'created': '2015-07-29 17:35:45.000000000', 'message': 'Refactor Import Tasks and its plugin dependency

The import task supports loading tasks from plugins. Currently,
the workflow is hardcoded for introspect & convert plugins, which
need ImportToFS task. This patch removes the dependency of
ImportToFS tasks from import workflow and moves it into these
plugins.

Also, we provide a utility function that can be used by the plugins
to load the ImportToFS tasks only once in the workflow.

TODO: Add spec reference

Change-Id: Ia6025695eeb014bad29ab1f2dd1fc12f717ece2f
'}]
commit_message:
Refactor Import Tasks and its plugin dependency

The import task supports loading tasks from plugins. Currently,
the workflow is hardcoded for introspect & convert plugins, which
need ImportToFS task. This patch removes the dependency of
ImportToFS tasks from import workflow and moves it into these
plugins.

Also, we provide a utility function that can be used by the plugins
to load the ImportToFS tasks only once in the workflow.

TODO: Add spec reference

Change-Id: Ia6025695eeb014bad29ab1f2dd1fc12f717ece2f

commit_message:
Merge tag '1.0.0'

This is a null-merge of the 1.0.0 release tag back into the master
branch so that the 1.0.0 tag will appear in the git commit history of
the master branch. It contains no actual changes to the master branch,
regardless of how our code review system's UI represents it. Please
ask in #openstack-infra if you have any questions, and otherwise try
to merge this as quickly as possible to avoid later conflicts on the
master branch.

Change-Id: I9f6bd68468f837c1f28e1428ef10d1562a5c1340

[{'created': '2015-10-18 19:06:02.000000000', 'message': "Additional RabbitMQ SSL fixes

This patch fixes two problems with RabbitMQ's SSL/TLS listener.

* When self-signed certificates are used, the CA cert isn't created, but it's
  included with the RabbitMQ server config anyway (bug 1507364).

* Self-signed certificates are owned by root within RabbitMQ's configuration
  directory and are unreadable by RabbitMQ. User-provided certificates aren't
  affected (bug 1506992).

Closes-bug: 1506992
Closes-bug: 1507364

Change-Id: If4f6a325eea4772f2fad4604785241b67adfaaf6
"}]
commit_message:
Additional RabbitMQ SSL fixes

This patch fixes two problems with RabbitMQ's SSL/TLS listener.

* When self-signed certificates are used, the CA cert isn't created, but it's
  included with the RabbitMQ server config anyway (bug 1507364).

* Self-signed certificates are owned by root within RabbitMQ's configuration
  directory and are unreadable by RabbitMQ. User-provided certificates aren't
  affected (bug 1506992).

Closes-bug: 1506992
Closes-bug: 1507364

Change-Id: If4f6a325eea4772f2fad4604785241b67adfaaf6

commit_message:
Validate task input only for import tasks

Currently, the validation for import task parameters
is done on all task types. It should only be done
for import tasks because each task type will have
its own validation.

Change-Id: I0b05d256545e93163bd2acf2a83222e7a969b927

commit_message:
Always drop lxc_net bridge configuration

This patch makes sure that the lxc_net play does always write the
LXC bridge-interface configuration regardless of it's admin state.
This is particular important after we deactivate the lxc-net
systemd script as part of the LXC network configuration.

Closes-Bug: #1507795
Change-Id: I9547fe02e20e8d1690340e1193b2453997ada25c

commit_message:
Move to keystone session object

ceilometer client is a rare client that doesn't allow to use
a keystoneclient/keystoneauth session object.

This change fixes that and will allow to remove the
deprecated apiclient code in the future.

Depends-On: I43223a8b38ff1f4ef30c1d2345a28de6ade51863
Depends-On: I7cbe0afa12c9d11ce2eaed1f4d29f41507e273f8
Change-Id: I4804c45c2ba69982163503ba5d9d4eba86f904fe

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-10-16 04:58:14.000000000', 'message': "Revise cluster_add_nodes action

Currently when adding nodes to a cluster, the nodes' identity(existance,
owned by whom, etc) are checked twice, this patch checks it before action
execution.
Also, allow cluster member to be added to the cluster again, just updated
the cluster's status, don't do anything.

Change-Id: Id35aee58dcb3294bca0e38de7df023960ad1b5ec
"}, {'created': '2015-10-16 05:03:14.000000000', 'message': "Revise cluster_add_nodes action

Currently when adding nodes to a cluster, the nodes' identity(existance,
owned by whom, etc) are checked twice, this patch checks it before action
execution.
Also, allow cluster member to be added to the cluster again, just updated
the cluster's status, don't do anything.

Change-Id: Id35aee58dcb3294bca0e38de7df023960ad1b5ec
"}, {'created': '2015-10-16 07:46:44.000000000', 'message': 'Allow cluster member nodes to be added to the cluster

Currently when a node is owned by a cluster, it is not allowed
to be added to any cluster. If user tries to add it to any cluster,
even to its owner, he will get the same error message
"Nodes xx owned by other cluster, need to delete them from those
clusters first."This will confuse user.
Also there is a case when user adds two nodes to a cluster, one is
already owned by the cluster, and the other is an orphan, in this case
he will be rejected and nothing will be done.
So it's better to allow the cluster-member node to be added to the cluster
again, but if in the adding node list there are some nodes owned by other
clusters, we deny this action.

Change-Id: Id35aee58dcb3294bca0e38de7df023960ad1b5ec
Closes-bugs: #1506759
'}, {'created': '2015-10-19 08:41:09.000000000', 'message': "Revise cluster_add_nodes action's behavior

This patch fixes the error message of adding a node which
is already in a cluster(no matter the cluster is target cluster
or not).
Also modify the way of node properties validation(don't remove
an element in a list by loop)
Thirdly, delete some redundant codes.

Change-Id: Id35aee58dcb3294bca0e38de7df023960ad1b5ec
Closes-bugs: #1506759
"}, {'created': '2015-10-20 02:43:09.000000000', 'message': "Revise cluster_add_nodes action's behavior

Also modify the way of node properties validation(don't remove

Thirdly, delete some redundant codes.

"}]
commit_message:
Revise cluster_add_nodes action's behavior

This patch fixes the error message of adding a node which
is already in a cluster(no matter the cluster is target cluster
or not).
Also modify the way of node properties validation(don't remove
an element in a list by loop)
Thirdly, delete some redundant codes.

Change-Id: Id35aee58dcb3294bca0e38de7df023960ad1b5ec
Closes-bugs: #1506759

Adds both the userguide and reference for consumers resource.
Currently only a register, delete and retrieve guide are
needed.

commit_message:
Add environments from manual cases in system tests

Environments configurations:
    - 1 Controller, 1 Compute, 1 Cinder on Neutron/TUN with Sahara
    - 1 Controller, 1 Compute, 3 Ceph, 1 Mongo on Neutron/TUN use Ceph
        Volume and Image with Ceilometer and Sahara
    - 1 Controller, 2 Compute, 1 Cinder, 3 Ceph, 1 Mongo on Neutron/VLAN
        use Ceph Image with Ceilometer
    - 1 Controller, 1 Compute, 1 Cinder, 3 Ceph on Neutron/VLAN use Ceph
        Image and Rados
    - 1 Controller, 1 Compute, 1 Cinder and Mongo, 2 Ceph on Neutron/VLAN
    use Ceph Image and Rados with Ceilometer

Change-Id: Ie60f8fafdc7580a621649e71823f611d97b6807d

commit_message:
Fix oslo.messaging+amqp1+dsvm to run from master

gate-tempest-dsvm-full-amqp1 ends up using oslo.messaging from
pip. We need a job that runs dsvm-full with oslo.messaging from git.
we reuse what was added for zmq in review:
If85ce9e4a6c976f30f29671e7d23eff784d0f5b8

and add the ostype parameter needed for the amqp1 job to run
only on fedora nodes

Change-Id: I40ac10040b9644cd74b4144fce77c34887f0f5b8

commit_message:
Make openstack-health npm lint job voting

We have finally gotten the lint checking into a good spot on
opnestack-health, so let's make the job voting so we're enforcing this
on new commits. It'll also validate that we can actually build the js
being submitted, which is something we're missing right now.

Depends-On: I3aa0c91e77f40c6383ac73850f5b93ebae9af323

Change-Id: Ie3d7326b8a3cc7f01d7ded174a0ac077e9695054

[{'created': '2015-10-08 11:06:43.000000000', 'message': 'This patch add device_owner while creating neutron port.

Signed-off-by: Pengfei Ni <feiskyer@gmail.com>
'}, {'created': '2015-10-08 14:23:10.000000000', 'message': "Add device_owner while creating neutron port.

Since horizon doesn't recognize kuryr resources, this patch fake
it as compute:nova instance.

Change-Id: Ib080ee59f6428732f341167088a99f726ef74891

Add device_owner while creating neutron port.

1. Set device_id to endpoint id
2. Set device_owner to kuryr:container

Closes-Bug: 1504001
Signed-off-by: Pengfei Ni <feiskyer@gmail.com>

commit_message:
Add check-requirements job for python-scciclient

This patch adds check-requirements job for python-scciclient in order
add to the project 'python-scciclient' [1] into projects.txt [2]
in accordance with "Project Creator's Guide" [3].

[1] https://github.com/openstack/python-scciclient
[2] https://github.com/openstack/requirements/projects.txt
[3] http://docs.openstack.org/infra/manual/creators.html

commit_message:
Write clouds.yaml to /etc as well

There are more than one user that need to access clouds.yaml values
in tests. Rather than copying the file everywhere, simply output
it to /etc/openstack.

However, we have things copying it at the moment, so output to
both places. A follow up patch will remove the homedir version.

Change-Id: I21d3c2ad7a020a5ab02dc1ab532feae70b718892

commit_message:
Support writing passwords to local.conf

localrc is deprecated for some time, but we still only try to write
passwords to this file.

Change-Id: I8d128eae97c6d0d8e347d1fe6f95b1e0a3d97fe5

commit_message:
Add compute personality feature config

Add personality config in compute-feature-enabled.
Remove using personality in general tests.
Add some tests to test_server_pesonality.
Change tests with personality to skip if disable.

Change-Id: Ieffa799949034b609b53c5c131d26bfe3cb83fa4

commit_message:
devstack: fix debug info for Gnocchi

Currently the gate job fails with:

2015-10-12 12:05:42.435 | * Unprocessed measures:
2015-10-12 12:05:42.448 | find: `/measures': No such file or directory

Because we didn't source the Gnocchi settings.

Change-Id: I35f2ea0d23a38d1cb514db72c2fe4bdf41c06f29

commit_message:
Make docstring of servers consistent

Docstring of service clients is very inconsistent, but we have a
plan to use it for generating API doc.
This patch makes docstring of servers consistent for fitting to
http://developer.openstack.org/api-ref-compute-v2.1.html
as a first step.

Change-Id: Icb51c2cf189fc17a91dcac5b95dc4a27afeac543

This sounds pretty good. One thing I'm concerned about though is that I will approve a spec and then code will take longer than expected to show or the review turnaround will be very slow. During that time other stuff is being starved and I'm twiddling my thumbs. 

If we give blueprints these exclusive priorities, I think we are going to need to be much more aggressive about bumping the slow ones out. Can you put some guidelines in here about how to handle that?"}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2015-10-16 05:57:35.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Workflow-1

We'll address your valid concerns in the next PS."}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2015-10-16 06:00:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

To give you a heads-up: I believe it's a role of the 'approver' to tag/pair up help the drafter/assignee have a quick turn around. It's a team work, and as such it requires collaboration by both parties. If no such collaboration is feasible/attained, the periodic pulse checked during regular updates should give us an early enough warning to take action. [{'created': '2015-10-16 00:36:40.000000000', 'message': "Improvements to the blueprint management process

It is easy to oversubscribe ourselves during a release
cycle. We approve specs only to experience that we fail
to review consistently; code is posted last minute,
we get lost into chasing race conditions, the odd dependency
throws the gate under the bus, and the ever-present cosmetic
refactoring patch steers our attention from what matters,
which is *reviewing what we commit to deliver*.

In order to keep ourselves focused on the bigger picture,
this patch proposes/formalizes changes to the way we
register blueprints so that we can improve our ability
to better foresee what we'll deliver at the end of a
release.

We obviously can't predict the future or chain people
to a desk, but a regular pulse check of a well planned
task list should at least help mitigate the feeding frenzy
that usually happens closer to FF. That inevitably
leads to half-baked and buggy solutions.

This patch also fixes minor bitrot due to lack of validation
(because of bug #1496882). In this case the fact that links
were broken down along multiple lines caused the errors.

Change-Id: Ia27b2a779204bf98c1dec2a30d00507de285f801

commit_message:
Improvements to the blueprint management process

It is easy to oversubscribe ourselves during a release
cycle. We approve specs only to experience that we fail
to review consistently; code is posted last minute,
we get lost into chasing race conditions, the odd dependency
throws the gate under the bus, and the ever-present cosmetic
refactoring patch steers our attention from what matters,
which is *reviewing what we commit to deliver*.

In order to keep ourselves focused on the bigger picture,
this patch proposes/formalizes changes to the way we
register blueprints so that we can improve our ability
to better foresee what we'll deliver at the end of a
release.

We obviously can't predict the future or chain people
to a desk, but a regular pulse check of a well planned
task list should at least help mitigate the feeding frenzy
that usually happens closer to FF. That inevitably
leads to half-baked and buggy solutions.

Change-Id: Ia27b2a779204bf98c1dec2a30d00507de285f801

commit_message:
Register oslo_service.wsgi options correctly

oslo_service 0.10.0 release added register_opts function to wsgi
module that is why it is no longer needed to access its private
_options module.

Change-Id: I4803a3540a6bc9c8f08db49e209668d0736abec7

Make profile related DB query project_safe

This patch makes profile related DB query interfaces project_safe
by default. load and load_all interfaces in profile based module
are also changed.

commit_message:
Add newlines at end of files

Add newlines at end of the files. Without the newline at the end of the
file the Gblame command in vim-fugitive gets confused.

These were the only three files discovered without newlines

Change-Id: I747e1ae35b2974732ec9058033a7ea445b08a121

commit_message:
Zone placement policy

This patch proposes a placement policy that spreads nodes across
availability zones based on the (default) weights of each zone. The zone
assignment is passed via node.data to profile layer and then to the nova
driver.

Change-Id: I0e10e13ef7d69fbdb837612df99efdbfdf9e4322
Co-Authored-By: Qiming Teng (tengqim@cn.ibm.com)
                Cindia-blue (lxinhui@vmware.com)

subject: Relax regex to avoid excluding tests from tempest plugins
messages:
[{'account_id': 6854, 'date': '2015-10-20 00:57:21.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 5196, 'date': '2015-10-20 01:01:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-2

This is not needed, we already have a separate tox entrypoint if you want to use a tempest plugin that does not do any regex filtering. 

The full job is specifically to run the tests from the integrated gate tempest job. We want the result to be repeatable regardless of the environment, polluting it with other tests is not desirable.'}, {'account_id': 6854, 'date': '2015-10-20 01:05:12.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Matthew,

my goal is to run fwaas scenario tests [1] on gate.
all-plugin includes slow tests, which i'm not sure is appropriate for gate.
how do you think?

commit_message:
Do not remove mapping if hdisk discovery fails

If the hdisk discovery fails with unknown udid, in that case
device name exist and udid is none, in that case connect volume
fails and no mappings are done, so during disconnect_volume we
should not try to remove the mappings for devices with unknown
udid.

Change-Id: If50b8d9cf7625d12afaeb76d6b7136262638a900
Closes-Bug: #1505388

WIP: N-Port Login changes for attach on shutoff VM

When attach request is made on VM which are in Powered off state
we need to temporarily Logged in the NPIV WWPNs to ensure proper
zoning on the fabric.

Closes-Bug: #1503797
'}]
commit_message:
Attach volume for power-off instances

For power-off instance the WWPNs are not logged in, hence the
volume attachment fails to fetch the fabric information. So the
proposed changes handle this scenario by creating the vfc_mappings
with the management partitions if the instance if power-off during
attach volume request.

Change-Id: I881a93ae10a709733b57c162e6ae79105c29a967
Closes-Bug: #1503797

commit_message:
Shared File Systems admin guide: remove local type of share network

A valid value of the network_type is VLAN, VXLAN, GRE, or flat.
The 'local' value was removed.

Change-Id: I86b51dbe37a6aa39ecc06362ae567a0a04f92df5
Closes-Bug: #1507626

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-10-14 00:53:06.000000000', 'message': 'Fix devuser pubkey defaults

Without this patch, the devuser element attempts to find public keys by
iterating over the string "rsa dsa". When two keys are grouped together
in quotes, a bash for loop treats it as a single key. You can see the
issue this causes when debug output is turned on:

   + for fmt in '"rsa dsa"'
   + '[' -f '/home/krinkle/.ssh/id_rsa dsa.pub' ']'

This is not a reasonably named key to look for, so this patch removes
the quotes so that the loop will look for id_rsa.pub and id_dsa.pub
separately.

Change-Id: I0b5b1abd14013de85d90e76a95918a8071a5e013
'}]
commit_message:
Fix devuser pubkey defaults

Without this patch, the devuser element attempts to find public keys by
iterating over the string "rsa dsa". When two keys are grouped together
in quotes, a bash for loop treats it as a single key. You can see the
issue this causes when debug output is turned on:

   + for fmt in '"rsa dsa"'
   + '[' -f '/home/krinkle/.ssh/id_rsa dsa.pub' ']'

This is not a reasonably named key to look for, so this patch removes
the quotes so that the loop will look for id_rsa.pub and id_dsa.pub
separately.

Change-Id: I0b5b1abd14013de85d90e76a95918a8071a5e013

commit_message:
Don't run dsvm tests on rst/unit test changes

If the change is only for rst file or unit test on tempest-lib, don't
run the dsvm changes for avoiding much test operation time.

Change-Id: I8797171640f05c2b04c4299fa2c05ba25684e2de

I'm still unclear on why we need this check in every method.  Shouldn't we just fail if the backend isn't accessible?  ie leave it up to the driver?

The fail over case is interesting (letting the manager do it instead of the driver) but I'm not sure how well that will work.

Anyway, I certainly don't object I'm just asking for some logic as to why these checks are now being sprinkled about."}, {'account_id': 5997, 'date': '2015-10-09 16:31:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

FWIW, these checks have been around for quite some time.   I think it's wise to ensure that the driver is ready to accept commands from the volume manager, re: initialized, as there is no point in calling the driver if it's known to be in a bad state.   

Our drivers check at startup, to make sure that it can talk to the backend, which comes from entries in cinder.conf.   If for whatever reason the driver checks at startup can't talk to the backend, then it's known to not be able to handle any request.  I'd like to not have to do these checks on every API entry point into the driver, hence the initialized flag, and the checks against that flag in the volume manager.   It's just a level of sanity."}, {'account_id': 11904, 'date': '2015-10-10 12:26:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

commit_message:
Ensure replication functions check driver status

This patch adds the missing checks to ensure
the driver's are initialized to both
enable_replication and disable_replication.

This patch also adds comment blocks to the
failover_replication as well as list_replication_targets
functions to explain why they are both are not
checking the driver for initialization.  One of the main
use cases for those 2 functions happen precisely when the
driver can't talk to the primary backend, but might be
able to talk to the secondary or target backends.

Change-Id: I4052e0ff4d2977ecfba940db56dba24c063bbbb6
Closes-Bug: #1501936

commit_message:
[sitemap] if last-modified not set in header use current date

This solves the following issue when last-modified is not set in the
response header:

---snip---
KeyError: 'Last-Modified'
---snap---

The new patch is shorter, restricted to Python 3 and use surrogateescape. It now looks good to me.

I don't know how oslo.rootwrap is consumed in applications. This patch changes the return type of the run_in_command(): it returned bytes for stdout/stderr and it now returns Unicode. I don't know which applications are impacted nor how this should be documented. It looks like the Python API is not documented at all :-(

http://docs.openstack.org/developer/oslo.rootwrap/index.html"}, {'account_id': 708, 'date': '2015-10-09 13:48:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

@Victor:

Python API is somewhat documented in spec and copied over to docs [1] 

It states that stdin, out and err are "strings" without specifying which ones they are. It should be corrected to "binary strings" everywhere, because it's not up to rootwrap to mangle with command input and output. It is not enforced in code (ducktyping and all), but it is verified in tests [2].

@fumihiko:

I don’t think this needs to be done in daemon code. As I said, code here expects binary strings and it should be tested. I don’t know how that test [2] passes here: we’re explicitly passing bytes in stdin and expect binary strings in return, so that should’ve failed with your changes.

Moreover, looking at change referenced in commit message [3] I can’t help but notice that you already convert everything to binary before calling out to daemon, so this change is redundant if not conflicting with what have been done on client side (in Neutron).

[1] http://docs.openstack.org/developer/oslo.rootwrap/usage.html#daemon-mode
[2] https://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack/oslo.rootwrap/tree/oslo_rootwrap/tests/test_functional.py#n74
[3] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/208848/5/neutron/agent/linux/utils.py,cm'}, {'account_id': 9107, 'date': '2015-10-09 13:57:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Yuriy Taraday: "I don’t think this needs to be done in daemon code. As I said, code here expects binary strings and it should be tested."

Since OpenStack applications are not deployed yet on Python 3, IMHO it's still ok to break the API. On Python 3, it's more "natural" to use Unicode strings. Using byte strings is more complex on Python 3. For example, you cannot just write "print(stdout)", it's wrong if stdout type is bytes.

In oslo.concurrency, I added an optional binary parameter with a default value to False. If it's True, stdout and stderr are returned as bytes. Maybe we should do that in the same patch.

"I don’t know how that test [2] passes here"

You can try to run tests with python3 -bb. For example, try PYTHON="python -bb" testr run --parallel in the virtual environment.'}, {'account_id': 708, 'date': '2015-10-09 13:59:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Ok, I see how this change passes Jenkins checks: there're no py3x check in pipeline. Where did it go?

I ran it locally, and most of tests fail with:

   TypeError('expect bytes or str, not NoneType')

(os.fsencode doesn't expect None) and the test I've referenced to fails with:

    MismatchError: b'teststr' != 'teststr'

which I've expected to happen."}, {'account_id': 9107, 'date': '2015-10-09 14:31:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: -Code-Review

Yuriy Taraday: "Ok, I see how this change passes Jenkins checks: there're no py3x check in pipeline. Where did it go?"

Oh wow, I expected oslo.rootwrap to be compatible with Python 3. I remove my vote. I prefer to wait until oslo.rootwrap has at least a non-voting Python 3 check job.

I wrote a patch to fix Python 3 issues in oslo.rootwrap: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/233093/'}, {'account_id': 708, 'date': '2015-10-09 15:11:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Just like in oslo.concurrency, I don't like that 'binary=True' API and I think we should honor exact representation that client wants to pass down to a command. But just as in oslo.concurrency, I think that's not a big deal (although such semantic uncertainty makes me toss and turn in sleep).

The problem here is inconsistency with already merged client code in Neutron. We should either stay binary-only or allow both unicode and binary strings with a flag that will be set to True in Neutron."}, {'account_id': 8344, 'date': '2015-10-11 23:49:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Yuriy,

Thank you for review.

daemon is not passed binary strings from neutron client.
You mistake a variable name in neutron/agent/linux/utils.py.

encoded data is set _process_input but execute_rootwrap_daemon is passed process_input without "_" to the head of it.

I'm going to modify tests.'}, {'account_id': 9107, 'date': '2015-10-15 11:05:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

commit_message:
Python 3: encode or decode i/o data of Popen.communicate()

In Python 3, input and output for Popen.communicate() is bytes type.
Therefore, encode input data and decode return data for Popen.communicate().

Change-Id: Id6d85eea4c771ac9756ef08ba80ebc09005fcc3e
Related Change-Id: I70f009e3366f0eeda5790652ea14f3627b934664

New version of oslo.db fixes a bug connected
with picklebility of engine facade.

commit_message:
Added periodic job for OpenStack-Ansible

This change adds a new job to test Kilo to Juno upgrades for
Openstack-Ansible and adds a new periodic job handler to zuul which
will notify the openstack-ansible mailing list on failure.

Note: this change will require the system-config entry for the
mailing list to merge for us to be able to recieve failure
notices. Pending review: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/224203

Change-Id: Ie9ee786d8cea9d34e2e0c2f669fd026abebed9d2

commit_message:
Sets upper boundaries for all of the oslo packages

This change to stable/liberty was in response to quite a few 
oslo releases that have caused deployment and stability issues.

Example error: http://bit.ly/1WYvfrM

The change sets the upper boundaries to ensure release 
stability

Change-Id: I9670c00a8cdfdc96687941d7083527bb5b55d6ee
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>

commit_message:
Preserve network interfaces order of vnfd template

The Python dictionary behavior of vnfd body does not guarantee the
network interfaces to be fetched in same order as specified in template.
This fix uses the third party python package tosca-parser to preserve
the order. This will ensure the interfaces come up in the same sequence
as specified in template.

Closes-Bug: #1504687
Change-Id: Ieddd2ba16328869cef901d94bb53dc9566c250df

commit_message:
puppet: retire beaker-upgrade jobs

beaker-upgrade jobs was really experimental and until now it never
really helped us in our CI & review process.

In the next cycle, we will push CI efforts to test OpenStack upgrades
with Puppet, but we don't know yet if it will be with Beaker or another
tool (our integration jobs are running in bash).

In the meantime, let's retire the jobs which are now useless.
They don't get attention and are quite unstable.

Change-Id: If2372fc3382d329ae7cff57b61f15f8d17083721

the master branch. It contains no actual changes to the master branch,

commit_message:
Merge tag '0.1.0'

This is a null-merge of the 0.1.0 release tag back into the master
branch so that the 0.1.0 tag will appear in the git commit history of
the master branch. It contains no actual changes to the master branch,
regardless of how our code review system's UI represents it. Please
ask in #openstack-infra if you have any questions, and otherwise try
to merge this as quickly as possible to avoid later conflicts on the
master branch.

Change-Id: I57e51262f64fab548375be61ab0f95d60c359cb6

commit_message:
Add flake8 to requirements

flake8 is called directly by dib-lint, so this is a hard requirement
to be installed for dib-lint to work outside of tox.  This came up
when proposing a dib-lint job for the nodepool elements in
project-config (I28459a9bbaaa6175d03dbe753498849a75942538)

Change-Id: I3052f860cebc66844cd21f34be64aea8474d2248

commit_message:
Update nova::db class to match other module pattern

This review aims to update the nova::db class to standardize it with the
other modules db classes[1][2]. It now offers the same parameters to customize
database connection behavior.

[1] https://github.com/openstack/puppet-neutron/blob/master/manifests/db.pp
[2] https://github.com/openstack/puppet-sahara/blob/master/manifests/db.pp

Change-Id: Ief978cd20a95c1ccafb7853ec8d5eb5d71513f7a

commit_message:
Remove POSIX users, groups, and file modes.

This patch removes the File resources of nova.conf for mode, user and
group which should be delivered by packaging tools.  These resources
(mode, user, and group attributes) could be in conflict with different
OS packaging systems which isn't a desired result.

Change-Id: I4fac32742dc317b16a6af825ad7095f0d94f3e57
Closes-Bug: #1458915

commit_message:
Introduce keystone::db class

Current modules[1][2][3] implements a
<component>::db class that is not implemented in keystone.

This commit aims to apply here the same logic.

[1] https://github.com/openstack/puppet-nova/blob/master/manifests/db.pp
[2]
https://github.com/openstack/puppet-designate/blob/master/manifests/db.pp
[3]
https://github.com/openstack/puppet-ceilometer/blob/master/manifests/db.pp

Change-Id: Ifb868c101dd516eda7b9826e0faf33c3bc296e02

commit_message:
Stop using deprecated tempest options

With the merge of 'Deprecate credential config options' in tempest,
(Change-Id: Ia5132c5cb32355d6f26b8acdd92a0e55a2c19f41)
admin credentials options have been moved from [identity] group to
[auth] group in tempest/config.py. This makes no difference for cinder
tempest tests.  However manila has separate tempest tests and
in manila_tempest_tests/tests/api/base.py, BaseSharesAdminTest always
gets admin credentials from identity group. It will fail with the
changed configuration options.

Closes-Bug: #1504052
Change-Id: If329a6563df2028a18c3fedea53065688e75339e

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

commit_message:
Integration tests - Instances tests

Added instancespage based on the new regions.
test_instances checks the instance createion and deletion.

Few other modifications I've made:
* forms:
- removed "div >" from checkbox locator, to identify "default" checkbox in
  "launch_instance->Access & Security ->default"
*horizon.conf
- Added [launch_instances] to include instances attributes from config file
*config
- Added InstancesGroup to include [launch_instances] from horizon.conf

Partially implements blueprint: integration-tests-hardening

Change-Id: I7d58a970fd36ff86021f3f050c5d01586a26599c

commit_message:
Introduce manila::db class

Current modules[1][2][3] implements a
<component>::db class that is not implemented in manila.

This commit aims to apply here the same logic.

[1] https://github.com/openstack/puppet-nova/blob/master/manifests/db.pp
[2] https://github.com/openstack/puppet-designate/blob/master/manifests/db.pp
[3] https://github.com/openstack/puppet-ceilometer/blob/master/manifests/db.pp

Change-Id: I803a5eacc7a81854e2bdd715785886c0f6cfbc33

commit_message:
Introduce ironic::db class

Current modules[1][2][3] implements a
<component>::db class that is not implemented in ironic.

This commit aims to apply here the same logic.

[1] https://github.com/openstack/puppet-nova/blob/master/manifests/db.pp
[2] https://github.com/openstack/puppet-designate/blob/master/manifests/db.pp
[3] https://github.com/openstack/puppet-ceilometer/blob/master/manifests/db.pp

Change-Id: I62fc13c749ff801daa7fb9701d4c12646272e1a3

commit_message:
Add hooks for external install & svc management

This adds defined anchor points for external modules to hook into the
software install, config and service dependency chain.  This allows
external modules to manage software installation (virtualenv,
containers, etc) and service management (pacemaker) without needing rely
on resources that may change or be renamed.

Change-Id: I032ee01505e0cbc125b0e219c436b77c93f57720

commit_message:
Update ceilometer::db class to match other module pattern

This review aims to update the ceilometer::db class to standardize it with the
other modules db classes[1][2]. It now offers the same parameters to customize database
connection behavior.

[1] https://github.com/openstack/puppet-neutron/blob/master/manifests/db.pp
[2]
https://github.com/openstack/puppet-sahara/blob/master/manifests/db.pp

Change-Id: Ic5ca33f862da300f4f429524ba488568d0608cf3

commit_message:
Introduce heat::db class

Current modules[1][2][3] implements a
<component>::db class that is not implemented in heat.
This commit aims to apply here the same logic

[1] https://github.com/openstack/puppet-nova/blob/master/manifests/db.pp
[2]
https://github.com/openstack/puppet-designate/blob/master/manifests/db.pp
[3]
https://github.com/openstack/puppet-ceilometer/blob/master/manifests/db.pp

Change-Id: I922260265d110d5823c546813ee125400ecc183d

commit_message:
Introduce gnocchi::db class

Current modules[1][2][3] implements a
<component>::db class that is not implemented in gnocchi.

This commit aims to apply here the same logic.

[1] https://github.com/openstack/puppet-nova/blob/master/manifests/db.pp
[2]
https://github.com/openstack/puppet-designate/blob/master/manifests/db.pp
[3]
https://github.com/openstack/puppet-ceilometer/blob/master/manifests/db.pp

Change-Id: I9bd224740740c3e587f4ae2c5e645d2ad5db98ba

commit_message:
Fix inconsistency in DHCPv6 hosts and options generation

The DHCP agent is inconsistent in how it handles subnets whose
ipv6_address_mode is not slaac.  While the DHCP agent writes out both
DHCPv6 host entries and DHCPv6 options for ports scoped by the subnet
for dnsmasq to use, subnet specific options are not written.

This patch addresses this inconsistency by generating subnet specific
options when the subnet's ipv6_address_mode is not slaac.

Closes-Bug: #1501451

Change-Id: I372c93fa5667e955c7b81181daa2e66f47d85fdf
(cherry picked from commit 81c5e511f704861a08f2e3938edca97474d4c44c)

commit_message:
Fix inconsistency in DHCPv6 hosts and options generation

The DHCP agent is inconsistent in how it handles subnets whose
ipv6_address_mode is not slaac.  While the DHCP agent writes out both
DHCPv6 host entries and DHCPv6 options for ports scoped by the subnet
for dnsmasq to use, subnet specific options are not written.

This patch addresses this inconsistency by generating subnet specific
options when the subnet's ipv6_address_mode is not slaac.

Closes-Bug: #1501451

Conflicts:
	neutron/tests/unit/agent/linux/test_dhcp.py

Conflict is due to the test file changed location in Kilo. Also added
_test_output_opts_file that was missing in Juno.

Change-Id: I372c93fa5667e955c7b81181daa2e66f47d85fdf
(cherry picked from commit 81c5e511f704861a08f2e3938edca97474d4c44c)

commit_message:
Fix inconsistency in DHCPv6 hosts and options generation

The DHCP agent is inconsistent in how it handles subnets whose
ipv6_address_mode is not slaac.  While the DHCP agent writes out both
DHCPv6 host entries and DHCPv6 options for ports scoped by the subnet
for dnsmasq to use, subnet specific options are not written.

This patch addresses this inconsistency by generating subnet specific
options when the subnet's ipv6_address_mode is not slaac.

Closes-Bug: #1501451

Change-Id: I372c93fa5667e955c7b81181daa2e66f47d85fdf
(cherry picked from commit 81c5e511f704861a08f2e3938edca97474d4c44c)

(2 comments)

It's not clear from the bug that this fixes anything. What state is the instance left in if network teardown fails, it's ignored, and then driver rollback executes? Isn't rollback still incomplete if the network on the destination wasn't torn down? Wouldn't the instance have network allocated on both the source and the destination in this case, with no indication to the user?"}, {'account_id': 14819, 'date': '2015-09-29 06:22:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Melanie, rollback_live_migration_at_destination is executed over rpc cast, so it's kind of "fire and forget". No notification for user would happen anyway, need to grep compute logs. Here is the problem that I'm trying to fix: live migration creates instance directory on destination node, which is cleaned only by rollback method that I've changed in this patch. If we don't give a chance to driver to make rollback, next attempt to live-migrate instance will fail earlier, as instance directory is already exists. As setup_networks_on_host belong only to nova network component I believe it's better to try execute driver's rollback, as dhcp lease will be cleaned after some amount of time anyway.
BTW, I'll decrease log level for this in next patchset. This looks reasonable, thanks to you and Markus.'}, {'account_id': 14819, 'date': '2015-09-29 08:02:42.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-09-29 09:00:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

commit_message:
Attempt rollback live migrate at dest even if network dealloc fails

When setup_networks_on_host fails during
rollback_live_migration_at_destination some resources are
left because driver.rollback_live_migration_at_destination
is not called.

To give driver a chance to cleanup resources,the network
method is wrapped with a try/except block so we can
attempt the rollback via the virt driver.

Closes-bug: #1488435

Change-Id: I463fa28fe05cf44dc335fe02f6c54d9b0a20d1e4

commit_message:
Exclude version 2.6.0 of oslo.util

A recent commit to oslo.util has caused the Trove tests to
break.  This looks to be addressed in a pending change request,
but in the mean time it should be excluded from the requirements.

Probable cause:
https://github.com/openstack/oslo.utils/commit/6010fb3fff11fc

Possible solution:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/230619

Change-Id: I487eae6da833151d8391f27097c4689d573af41f

commit_message:
Enable py3 jobs on networking-cisco

This patch enables python 3 jobs on networking-cisco and makes the
requirements-check non-voting until the cisco requirements are merged
into global requirements successfully.

Change-Id: Ifbecfc6abc0cb3d42e0432ee4783903e41347d66

[{'created': '2015-10-19 00:49:45.000000000', 'message': "Redirect on 303 in SAML plugin

The SAML plugin handles redirects in a custom manner but currently only
checks for the 302 redirect code. This doesn't cover the mod_auth_mellon
case which responds with a 303.

commit_message:
Redirect on 303 in SAML plugin

The SAML plugin handles redirects in a custom manner but currently only
checks for the 302 redirect code. This doesn't cover the mod_auth_mellon
case which responds with a 303.

Also handle the 303 redirect case.

Change-Id: Idab5f381fcbfb8c561184845d3aa5c8aab142ecd
Closes-Bug: #1501918

commit_message:
Updated the neutron l3HA tool to use v3

The change adds Keystone v3 support to neutron l3 ha tool. This
change is needed to ensure that all l3-ha fail overs are
accomplished correctly.

The tool has been updated to skip / support routers that have
already bene setup using the built in neutron L3HA.

This is something that will need to be backported to Kilo

Change-Id: I94f21ff3fa511bc9da6b57cdf847719620818ece
Closes-Bug: #1499708
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>

* Converts volume v2 tests to use Identity v3 so domains can be tested
* Add volume list (v2) tests for new options

commit_message:
Follow-on for volume list - add tests, clean help

* Add volume list tests for v1 (a copy of the v2 tests)
* Converts volume v2 tests to use Identity v3 so domains can be tested
* Add volume list (v2) tests for new options
* Re-orders volume list options (both v1 and v2) to match
* MArks the new volume list (v2) options as v2-only in doc

Change-Id: I2181b2c48cfde2147d7d0ef135322df8a81e7ce8

This is in a better shape, but I'd really like feedback on two items before moving on:

a) I've managed to get autorequire in the custom type to work, but this has some issues. I had to use Facter to ensure a different package is installed for Debian / RedHat families. This works ok, although it creates a problem in the spec test. 

Basically, the type seems to be loaded only once and _before_ running any test, so it does not matter how I stub the fact in the test, it always uses the same one. I have been able to work around it with the usage of Puppet::Type.rmtype(:swift_object_expirer_config), but according to [1] this should not be used. My gut feeling is that I am making too complicated just to avoid an explicit require, so I'd go back to the previous implementation unless there is a very strong reason not to. Happy to hear comments about is.

b) Due to the packaging differences between Debian and Red Hat, I need to check for the presence of package['openstack-swift-proxy'] in the manifest (for Red Hat platforms), and declare it if it is not present. This allows setting up object-expirer on a Red Hat system even if it is not a proxy server itself.

However, this introduces a side effect: if swift::objectexpirer and swift::proxy are included in the same manifest, and swift::objectexpirer is declared first, I get a duplicate package definition. This is expected, although I cannot simply make package['swift-proxy'] optional in swift::proxy because some dependencies will fail then.

So my question is: is this an acceptable tradeoff (documenting swift::proxy needs to be first), or is there a better way to get this done?


[1] http://www.rubydoc.info/gems/puppet/Puppet%2FMetaType%2FManager%3Armtype"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-08-21 14:13:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Verified+1

commit_message:
Add support for swift-object-expirer service

The swift-object-expirer service was not supported by
puppet-swift. Adding support by creating a new class
(swift::objectexpirer), and its associated custom type/provider.

Change-Id: I498ffe525a7316c0091e4c9d8b7d9658234231f6
